						               													<description>&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#149;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#167;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#164;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#144;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#170;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#131;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#136;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#158;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#188;&amp;#227;&amp;#130;&amp;#177;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#131;&amp;#227;&amp;#131;&amp;#136; (Favorite Market) is a card game from Japan, with players tweeting out their influence.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;During a high school festival, students want their favourite food stalls to succeed. So they use their tweets and followers to promote themselves and their trends, through stealth marketing. Players can like tweets and retweet, and try to make the festival more exciting.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The players have a personal trend and combine this with a stall to create up to 20 different combinations. They each secretly support three of the stalls.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;There is a deck of tweets (using the actual twitter accounts from the doujin circle and their friends), and retweet cards. By playing tweets, liking and retweeting, they can promote the stalls they support.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;On a player's turn, they get to do any two actions from three (same action if they like):&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Choose one of the three posts on the common timeline and 'Like' it to apply the card effect.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Refresh the timeline, which turns on new posts and removes old ones from the timeline.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;'Retweet', which brings back to the timeline a post that was liked in the past, although its use is limited.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;As they players perform the actions, their stock of customers goes down. The game ends when all the customers are gone.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The player who earns the most points wins the game by comparing the number of customers in their supporting shop, secretly decided at the beginning of the game, and finally adding up the bonuses for meeting special conditions.&amp;#10;user summary&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
